title: Arcade Coindoor Lock Replacement with Credit Button

description.text:
Arcade Coin-door Lock replacement that adds a credit button without the need to drill a hole in your game or hack other wires!

When I buy a game, I usually remove the locks altogether. This hasn't been great when toddlers are over, and I have had mixed success adding coin wires to the player 2 buttons or other use. Thanks to the original knurled nut design by akira3dp0, I tweaked it to suit my needs and designed a simple cam to hold the door closed.

I used these buttons with marginal success - Soldering iron would melt the plastic quickly. https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00OJZPMD2

30mm bolt works great for most bally/midway games. The 50mm bolt seems to work better with pinball.

[for best results]

  • After printing, hand-thread the knurled nut to the bolt a couple times to ensure a good fit. Then solder 2 wires to the button, pass the wires through the bolt, then use hot-glue to both insulate the connections and hold the button to the bolt.

  • Remove all nuts and parts from the previous lock. All you need is the bolt, the nut, and the cam. You might want to hot glue or superglue the cam to keep it from moving once you install everything.

  • Attach the wires to the coin credit switch, and you're all set!

I have a very nice Knock box...to which I recognize the talents of Mr. DonJorhe. It is the perfect size and the styling is very nice.

I saw that if I was a bit overzealous with my knocking...I worried that I might dislodge the bar from one end or the other. This REMIX is in 3 parts. Two outer knobs...and the main bar. It's designed to be printed in ABS, and the knob without threads...to be welded to the flat end of the bar with acetone. Once welded together...the threaded end can be inserted into the Knock box...and the other knob screwed on gently. It should erase any fear of the bar coming dislodged, whilst maintaining the ability to disassemble for cleaning or bar replacement, should it eventually require that from use.

The bar wound up being about 6mm too long. So, if you want a tighter fit...you can take 6mm off the flat end of the bar before printing.

title: Centre Drill Jig for Tubes / Round Bars

description.text:
This jig is designed to help to cross drill holes centrally in pipe / tube / round bar stock. It has three 2mm diameter holes in the top and bottom halves. The idea is to clamp the lower half in a machine vise, put a 2mm drill bit in a bench drill, align the drill bit with one of the holes (by moving the vise), lock the vise to the table, insert the tube (optionally add the top half to help locate the tube) and drill on that axis.

I've also used this successfully with a hand drill and without a vise, so a bench drill isn't a necessity. Take it easy, and remove the drill a few times to clear the swarf. After drilling a 2mm pilot hole all the way through, you can incrementally drill up to the final size needed.

This would suit tube from about 6mm to 12mm diameter. Using only the base section, you could go up to 22mm.

title: Spool Shelf using 3/4" EMT & 8x10 Metal Shelf Brackets

description.text:
Update to Two Part version 2/6/2017
I updated the 2 part version so it would not extend past the widest part of the metal bracket.
The 2 part brackets will fit on a 110mm x 110mm print bed or larger. The 1 part will fit on a 180mm x 170mm print bed or larger.

I got tired of just having my spools laying on a shelf. I have a nice 3' space above the door which was not being utilized which seemed like the perfect place to put these rolls.

I looked at several designs & started to remix http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:6544 to use 1/2" or 3/4" Electrical Conduit, but I was not sure how well those plastic corners would hold up even though it is not a lot of weight from the plastic spools. While thinking of ideas, it occurred to me that I could use those inexpensive 8"x10" shelf brackets, but use them upside down from the way they are intended. Think I paid $1.32 for each metal bracket at Walmart. I initially made each bracket in 2 parts, but ended up using a 1 piece bracket. One of my brackets is in in the corner of the room & the 2 piece bracket would not work unless I moved the metal bracket 1/2" away from the corner. The 2 part brackets extend about 5 - 6mm beyond the edge of the bracket in order to get a dovetail joint to work.

Originally I was going to use 1/2" EMT (Electrical Metal Tubing), but thought 1/2" might flex a little in the middle. Since I also had some 3/4" EMT laying around from the mostly printed CNC project, I decided to use that instead. The attached openscad files allow you to change it to use 1/2" EMT, 1/4" EMT or 1/2" PVC or some other size. Just change the variable EMT_OD = 23.5; to the diameter you want to use. After test fitting the one piece version, I added a little ridge support on the outer edges of the middle of the bracket to make it less flimsy.

For the dovetail joints, I used a clearance of .3, but have options for .4 or .2mm clearance. Just change the variable Dove_Size = 3; to 4 for .4 or 2 for .2 clearance.

There are 3 different types you can use. I used the Clamped type on One end & the NoClamp type on the other. If you are doing a really long shelf, you can use the HalfHt version for the middle bracket.
EMT_SpoolShelf_OnePiece_Clamped_Rev22.stl
EMT_SpoolShelf_OnePiece_NoClamp_Rev22.stl
EMT_SpoolShelf_OnePiece_HalfHt_Rev22.stl

EMT_SpoolShelf_OnePieceTestSize_Rev22.stl (Test print for size)

The One Piece bracket will easily fit on an 8" print bed.

Most of the filament rolls I use are 200mm in Diameter, but I test fit a 240mm roll & that easily fit also. I can get 11 rolls on this 3' shelf.

Hardware I am using
6 - M5x10mm Socket Head Cap Screws to fasten plastic clamps to metal bracket
6 - #10 x 1-1/2" wood screws to mount metal shelf bracket to the wall
2 - 3/4"x36" EMT (Electrical Metal Tubing)
2 - M3x20mm Socket Head Cap Screws with Locknuts if using the Tightening clamp option

I used http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:940458 for the end caps on the 3/4" EMT.

I enclosed a few photos of how this all goes together along with a photo of the metal shelf bracket with its part information listed so you will get the correct one. I would print the EMT_SpoolShelf_OnePieceTestSize_Rev22.stl to check for size. This part is only 1mm high.

Since all the vertical supporting structure is on the metal shelf brackets, I printed these parts at 20% infill using eSun PLA+ Silver.

title: Surface-mount wall box for one keystone ethernet jack and one pair of PowerPoles, with side-mounting captive nuts

description.text:
There is a cheap way of handling power over ethernet: use two of the twisted pairs within a Cat 5 cable for power, and two pairs for half-duplex Ethernet. (See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_over_Ethernet#Pinouts for the wiring.) This box provides a neat way of having DC and Ethernet connectors side-by-side, and also holds captive clip nuts of a particular type, which can be used to bolt something to the side of the box (camera, some sort of sensor or whatever). I use it with http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1644939 to mount a radiation monitor. The captive nuts are the same as you would use for rack-mounting equipment to a steel 19" rack, which take a 10/32 bolt. Like this: https://www.amazon.com/10-32-Rack-Mounting-Steel-Carton/dp/B0012XRVYC

The captive nut spacing is 26mm, and they will be 8mm away from the wall. So you can design anything you like with holes with matching spacing, and mount it to the side of this box.

title: Range control knob spacer (for LG range)

description.text:
These are spacers and (temporary) storage for the front-end control knobs for an LG LDE4415ST range.

The cooktop elements are turned on by pushing inward on the control knobs and turning the knob. The knobs are quite sensitive and it's very easy to turn on the cooktop elements by mistake (bumping into them, reaching over the cooktop, etc.). This design was prompted to protect against accidentally turning on the elements (which indeed happened to me just before I created this design).

The spacers fit between the knob and the front panel to prevent pushing the knobs. Made for easy insertion or removal, and fits fairly comfortably (not perfect, but sufficient). Do not remove the know and place the spacer--simply insert it through the top-end, as shown in the pictures.

(NOTE: if placed before while the knob is off, the knob can still be pushed and turned with the spacer in between--I haven't looked into this more carefully as sliding it into place is sufficient.)

The box is for temporary storage for the spacer while cooking (i.e., to keep it out of the way).

description.text:
Don't download and print this if you can't SAFELY change out an outlet cover. If you die and I find out I might think about maybe one day feeling kinda bad, possibly.

This is a standard electrical outlet cover with a built-in shelf. I made the shelf the same depth as my Moto 4G Plus is wide so I could plug in my phone charger and set it on the shelf. Remix to your heart's content just remember to give attribution as I did to the design I shamelessly modified to make it 'mine'.

There's three variations:
Shelf without a lip -- can be mounted top or bottom.
Shelf with the lip on top -- should be mounted with the shelf on top so the phone doesn't slide off the front.

title: Poly-Snaps: Tiles for Building Polyhedra
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
These tiles snap together to make polyhedra of any type you wish! Regular, semi-regular, truncated, stellated, or freaky; you decide. Customize your own with the "Open in Customizer" button or download pre-made sets of compact or light Poly-Snap tiles. The compact tiles are the blue, white, and black ones in the main picture; they are sturdy and difficult to snap together, so they make very strong models you can toss around. The light tiles are larger and shown in the red picture; these are easier to take apart and put together and print up very quickly, but the models are a little less sturdy. Depending on your printer and the filament, temperature, elevation from sea level, day of the week, etc, you may need different tolerances for your snaps; you can modify this in the Customizer.
A few technical notes and tips are listed in the Instructions tab. Detailed walkthroughs of how we used OpenSCAD to make Poly-Snaps to construct particular models are at the links below.
Truncated Tetrahedron
Octahedron
Truncated Octahedron
Snub Cube
Icosidodecahedron
Icosahedron

Unlike the tiles we used in http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:185859, these Poly-Snap tiles all have identical snap configurations. As long as you are trying to build an orientable surface this one configuration will suffice. The only trick is to make sure you don't attach them in the wrong orientation. On a Replicator 2 the Poly-Snaps print with a shiny side and a matte side; keep one type of finish on the inside of the model and one on the outside, and all your tiles will line up correctly. You may have to snap and un-snap the tiles a few times to break them in; they get a bit looser over time. A pair of pliers can help snap them together the first time, if needed. We suggest making the border size close to the thickness. Because of the way this model was constructed, you can't make completely solid tiles, and because of reality you can't have the border be larger than the radius, so make sure your border is small enough to fit within the tile. In our experience, clearance works well between .1 and .2, and lengthen works well between .3 and 1.2. =====

description.text: Although the Galaxy Nexus Dock by tlipoma ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:15805 ) is solid and has served me well, there were some problems that were nagging me: Problem #1: My phone didn't sit snug--it would wobble around. This is tantamount to "wonk", which should be avoided at all costs. Problem #2: The USB cable would not stay in the channel that runs out the back of the dock. It would come out if I undocked, and I would have to manually align the cable with the channel every time I wanted to re-dock the phone. Problem #3: My phone doesn't do anything cool and "docky" when I dock my phone!!! I want dock mode!!! Solution to #1: Get some Sugru and wedge it into the corners of your dock. Wet the Sugru down with soapy water, dock your phone, undock your phone, and let the Sugru cure. Thanks, Sugru! http://sugru.com/ Solution #2 to #1 (not implemented here): Make some adjustments to tlipoma's Dock2.stl in OpenSCAD or something. This is a lame solution to be posted in a derivative, as tlipoma should adjust the dock width himself and post in his thing page. Hey! Your Galaxy Nexus is the same width as mine, tlipoma! You should be feeling this pain as well! Solution to #2: Put some cable guide clips in there. This works amazingly well, and was a no-brainer to add to tlipoma's design. Solution to #3: Put an NFC sticker on the dock's backrest and write some Android code that performs some cool "docky" actions when it detects the NFC tag. Note: Please contact me if you want to see my android code. It's pretty straightforward if you know your Android API, but a nightmare if you are a beginner. My example code will help. :)

I printed this with my Tom + MK7 + HBP with the following Print-O-Matic settings:
  • Nozzle heat = 225
  • HBP heat = 115

  • of Walls: 0

  • Infill: 25% (feel free to experiment)
  • Layer height: .3 mm
  • Speed: 30 mm/s
  • Print
  • Apply Sugru to inside corners of dock
  • Apply soapy water to the Sugru
  • Dock your phone
  • Undock your phone
  • Add Sugru to the base (make little rubber feet) (optional, but you've already opened the Sugru packet, and you have some Sugru left over, so you might as well)
  • Wipe off all soapy water
  • Let your Sugru cure
  • If need be, use a little hot glue to keep your USB plug in place
  • Dock your phone.
  • Rock out with your dock out!!!
    • Note #1:I added a cord clip I bought at Walgreens to the back for easy cord storage.
    Note #2:I added an NFC sticker to the dock's backrest and wrote an Android app to perform some docking actions once the phone is docked and senses the NFC tag. If you are interested in this, leave a note and I'd be happy to share my (unpublished) NFC Android code with you!

description.text:
Last year I had a local prototype shop produce 8 of these props using the SLA process. Needing a propeller solution for one of our micro FPV machines, this is what I ended up with.

The SLA prints were nice quality (at about $8.50 each) but very fragile and not functional. Also they are too fine to be molded. Injection molding is probably the way but these are fun to play with. The center hole fits a 1mm shaft such as the common brushed motors.

I say experiment with your particular printer and see what kind of quality you can get. I was impressed that they printed as well as the did and made my wife a miniature wind turbine using one of these props.

description.text:
I try to design from a purist standpoint, with as little glue and non-printed parts as possible. So I try to print snap-fit parts, which works fine if you can print your flexible parts horizontally. But when it comes to round pegs, it is difficult to print the notched snap-fit pegs you find in commercial projects. When printed, the flexible tabs tend to snap along the layer lines instead of flexing properly.

So, my designs, such as the modified prankapult, have been incorporating c-clips. They allow the round (or even square) pegs to have more width since they don't have to be flexible themselves, and still hold everything together.

I design mostly in Sketchup, and it has serious issues with precision and has no boolean support. This makes it difficult to properly shape the cutout for the c-clips and I finally got tired of fiddling with it.

So, I wrote an openScad (and openJScad if anyone is interested) version so I could make a clip of any size I needed without spending so much time tweaking vertices in sketchup. If you use a decent cad program, it's probably not a big deal to make it from scratch. The peg isn't a big deal even in sketchup, but I've included a file for it as well (since customizer only allows one scad file per "thing", the peg is here). The peg it generates isn't meant to be used a model itself, it is meant to be imported into sketchup and merged with whatever geometry you already have.

When printing the clip, I use 100% fill and concentric patterns for infill and top and bottom. This should allow the most stability during flexing, as very little force will be in a direction trying to separate strands.

description.text:
I recently purchased a Honeywall/Adempco Vista 20p security system and an Envisalink 3 module to connect it to my network. The Envisalink 3 comes with 3 mounting pegs to mount it to the Vista enclosure. Unfortunately, the enclosure I received seems to be a different model from what the envisalink was designed for, and no holes lined up. I could have drilled new ones, but didn't want to deal with metal shavings, or sharp-edged holes. And if I had been off by just a little with one hole, I'd have probably been drilling 3 new holes to keep my screwed up one from interfering.

So, instead, I made this adapter plate. It has 3 holes that hold the envisalink pins in the proper locations to mount the circuit board. On the other side, it has 3 pegs that align with 3 holes I found on the enclosure. Those pegs are notched to fit my customizable c-clips to hold it in place.

When assembling it, the pegs that come with the envisalink should stick out one way, and the 3d printed pegs should stick out the other. If your pegs are all on the same side, you put them in backwards.

Update
When I finally installed the system, I realized that the mounting holes I had chosen are in the way of the battery. If you somehow install the enclosure in a different orientation, or if your battery is remote and not sitting on the bottom of the enclosure, this will work fine. Otherwise, I am working on finding a new mounting location and designing a new adapter, and will update this when I am done

description.text:
Venus de Polylactide is my first attempt at a BJD or "ball-jointed doll". Frankly, I'm not too pleased with the outcome (too much range of motion in some joints, too little in others, and I only figured out how to hollow out the pieces properly after I'd already finished it), but who knows, someone might find her useful.

I used MakeHuman to model the base form, Meshmixer to slice into segments, and Tinkercad to create the joints.

To print:

  • You may print the entire model at once using the "Single_Plate.STL" file, but this may limit your fine control over which parts get supports and infill.
  • Supports are only necessary for the hands. Keep them sparse (I used 10%) to minimize scarring.
  • Use a thick brim to hold the limb segments stable during printing
  • For most parts little infill is needed. For the hands, I recommend 100%.
  • As with anything, 0.1mm resolution is pretty, but this will take a long time to print anyway so you might stick to 0.2mm as I did here.

To assemble:

  • Use 2-3mm elastic cord, sold at craft or hobby shops
  • You will need a fine wire (I use a violin "A" string, taped to the cord) to thread the cord through the limbs. This is tricky and time consuming. You may want to drill out the holes bigger to ease the process.
  • Begin in pelvis by passing the cord from one hip joint to the other. Then thread down one leg to the foot and back up, back through the hip joint and out the pelvis top. Repeat with the other leg. Grab both ends of your cord, pull hard, and tie a small knot. You will pass this knot back into the pelvis, to keep tension in the legs. Then pass the two loose ends up through the torso, out their respective arms, down to the wrist, back through the arms and shoulder joints, and finally up through the neck into the head. Pass one end through the loop in the head, yank hard to apply tension, tie off and you're done.
  • Glue the head cap on with the cement of your choice.

You are invited to remix and distribute Venus de Polylactide in whatever ways you see fit, provided you clearly reference this original design. If you think of it, send me a message on Thingiverse so I can check out what she's become.

title: "Mistral" Extruder Cooling Duct for the Anet A8 Printer

description.text:
I've been designing and printing all kinds of cooling ducts for the last 2 months as I just wasn't happy with what I had. Even the popular round ducted coolers just don't do a good job in directly cooling the filament whilst keeping the heat block hot. Also many found on the net are too clunky, too heavy or are IMHO just terribly designed.
With the new Marlin and other 3D printer firmware's incorporating thermal protection mechanism it now becomes even more important to have a design that will not cause false alarms. This is particularly the case when the cooling ducts blow air on the heat block and not on the filament.

Design objectives:

  • Blow high volume air on the filament just beyond the nozzle.
  • Avoid as much as possible in getting cooling air on the nozzle/heat block.
  • Create a design that will not disrupt the view surrounding the nozzle.
  • Make it easy to get to the nozzle with tweezers to remove filament.
  • Create a version that can easily be printed.
  • Make it as light as possible to avoid high mass on the extruder. It weighs 2.8 grams.

At the end of the day I have found that this design outperforms anything I had been testing so far.

Attention:

  • This cooling duct is intended for use with the standard unmodified A8 printer.
  • It is recommended that the cooler be printed in ABS or PETG as these filaments are more heat resistant. However I have mine printed in PLA without any issues. When printing ABS or high temp filaments I just remove the cooler. You normally don't print with the fan on for high temp filaments.
  • With this cooler you might need to reduce airflow with some prints! Sometimes I have to print with 75% or less where in the past air flow was set to 100%.

I want to thank Jan Hedström for testing this cooling duct and confirming the effectiveness.
Also thanks for the idea of giving it a cool name "Mistral"!

Please let me know if you have a problem with the design so I can improve it if necessary.

Also please post a picture with comments if you have made one.

Thanks.

Leo

If you are using SkyNet3D then you can use a function to calibrate your extruder nozzle via „PID Autotuning“.
You will already find PID values in the firmware however it is a good idea to set them according to your surroundings.

This is how to calibrate the hotend:

First we need to get the PID values from the hotend. The values are read in 8 cycles using the following code:

M106
M303 E-0 S210 C8

Code description:

  • M106 run nozzle at 100%
  • M303 start PID autotuning
  • E-0 select the first hotend
  • S210 set extruder temperature. Here we chose 210°C
  • C8 denotes the number of cycles. In this example 8

After the 8 cycles have completed you will see something like this:

Kp 14.68
Ki 0.70
Kd 76.59

Now you will need to save the values to the printers eeprom:

M301 P14.68 I0.70 D76.59
M500

Code description:

  • M301 temporary sets the PID values
  • P = Kp
  • I = Ki
  • D = Kd
  • M500 will save the temporary PID values to eeprom.

More information can be found here: http://reprap.org/wiki/PID_Tuning

Update 15.2.2017

I've added a thicker walled (1.2mm) version 1.0a to the files section. In my opinion the standard (0.8mm) thick version 1.0 is best used, however some users have asked for a "beefier" cooling duct.

Update 19.2.2017

I've uploaded a new version "Mistral 2" as an alternative depending on your needs: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2121279

title: Filter Floss Basket for Fluval Spec V Saltwater Conversion

description.text:
The popular Fluval Spec V aquarium can be easily adapted to a saltwater reef tank. However, the stock foam insert isn't exactly ideal for saltwater since you want to maximize water flow and you really don't need that much mechanical filtration.

The tank runs just fine without the foam insert entirely, but at the expense of particles floating around in the water column. To remove this while minimally disturbing the already compromised flow from the pump, I've come up with a basket that attaches to the sump grills and will hold polyester filter floss. This filter floss can be easily accessed for rinsing off periodically.

Notes:

I printed this in PETg at 100% infill. You should avoid PLA if your tank's pH is higher than 7.8.

There are two versions, one is larger.
